The administration also moved to widen its surveillance net. The IRS neared an agreement to share confidential tax data with ICE to locate undocumented immigrants, an \'93unusual, if not unprecedented\'94 breach of the traditional firewall around tax records. The State Department ordered consular officers to comb social media for signs of support for terrorism when reviewing student visas, with a standard broad enough to catch pro\uc0\u8209 Palestinian activism or criticism of U.S. policy. Plans were floated to inspect the social media accounts of green card and citizenship applicants for \'93hostile attitudes.\'94 At the same time, funding was cut for a national database tracking domestic terrorism, hate crimes, and school shootings. The result was a surveillance regime that looked hard at vulnerable populations while turning its gaze away from threats that did not fit the administration\'92s narrative. Visibility flowed one way.\
