Inside the federal workforce, the week marked a sharp turn against organized labor and neutral administration. On March 27, Trump signed executive orders that stripped collective bargaining rights from hundreds of thousands of federal workers. One order cited national security to exempt entire departments\'97State, Defense, Homeland Security, and others\'97from the Federal Labor-Management Relations Program. Another directed agencies to cease engaging in collective bargaining, terminate existing agreements, and stop deducting union dues from paychecks. The Office of Personnel Management followed with instructions to implement these changes. In parallel, reports surfaced of plans to cut between 8% and 50% of staff across major agencies, including Housing and Urban Development, Interior, the IRS, and HHS. The civil service was being thinned and politicized at once.\
