These were not abstract reorganizations. The Social Security Administration\'92s website crashed under the strain of reduced staffing, and new rules forced beneficiaries without internet access to verify their identity in person. Acting SSA Commissioner Leland Dudek threatened to shut down the agency in response to a court order limiting DOGE\'92s access to sensitive records, framing judicial oversight as a threat to benefits. When a federal judge issued a temporary restraining order barring DOGE from SSA databases, the agency responded by installing a former DOGE operative, Scott Coulter, as its Chief Information Officer. On paper, Coulter was now an SSA employee; in practice, the appointment looked like an attempt to circumvent the court\'92s order and keep DOGE\'92s hand on the data. The civil service, once designed as a buffer between politics and administration, was being politicized and hollowed out. Neutral competence was treated as an obstacle.\
