Public health and social welfare were hit from another angle. Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. announced plans to cut 10,000 jobs from HHS, close half its regional offices, and consolidate functions into a new \'93administration for a healthy America.\'94 At the same time, HHS canceled more than $12 billion in grants to states for mental health services, addiction treatment, and infectious disease tracking, and pulled back over $11 billion in COVID\uc0\u8209 19 funds. Vaccine skeptic David Geier, disciplined in the past for practicing medicine without a license, was hired to lead a federal study on vaccines and autism. Kennedy himself spread dubious claims about vaccine risks, contributing to measles outbreaks and declining trust in health agencies. The cuts and appointments did not simply shrink government; they redirected it away from evidence-based care and toward ideological projects. Stewardship gave way to experiment.\
