The same impulse appeared in the capital\'92s streets. An executive order created the \'93DC safe and beautiful task force,\'94 chaired by Stephen Miller, to coordinate federal and local enforcement of immigration laws and to \'93beautify\'94 Washington. The order authorized the removal of homeless encampments and graffiti from federal lands, the expansion of law enforcement presence, and the acceleration of concealed weapon permits. A parallel order, \'93Making the District of Columbia Safe and Beautiful,\'94 reinforced these aims. On paper, the task force was about safety and aesthetics. In practice, it extended federal authority into local policing, targeted immigrants and the unhoused, and gave a senior White House aide a platform to reshape the capital\'92s public space in line with the administration\'92s priorities. Public order became a canvas for power.\
