When the leak became public, the administration\'92s response was to minimize and deflect. Intelligence chiefs testified before House and Senate committees, insisting that no classified information had been shared, even as published messages suggested otherwise. Trump refused to fire Waltz or Hegseth, reportedly to avoid giving the appearance of admitting fault or granting a victory to the press. A watchdog group, American Oversight, sued officials for violating the Federal Records Act by using auto\uc0\u8209 deleting messages for official business. Chief Judge Boasberg issued a temporary restraining order requiring preservation of all messages in the chat. The administration invoked the state secrets privilege in related litigation, signaling that it would not provide further information. Meanwhile, Der Spiegel reported that email addresses and passwords of officials involved in the chat were available in hacked data dumps, raising the specter of foreign exploitation. The episode showed how chaos\'97conflicting statements, overlapping investigations, and secrecy claims\'97could be used to blur accountability rather than to protect security.\
