Private power, especially that of Elon Musk, threaded through many of these stories. Musk\'92s Department of Government Efficiency had already driven deep cuts in federal staffing. This week, the FBI created a task force to investigate vandalism at Tesla dealerships and charging stations, and Attorney General Pam Bondi announced terrorism\uc0\u8209 related charges against individuals accused of damaging Tesla property. Trump compared Tesla vandalism unfavorably to the January 6 attack on the Capitol, calling for severe penalties. Protests against Musk\'92s influence, organized under the banner \'93TeslaTakedown,\'94 drew both peaceful demonstrators and violent counterattacks from Trump supporters, including assaults with a car and a taser. At the same time, Musk\'92s PAC poured $19 million into a Wisconsin Supreme Court race, offering $100 payments and a $1 million prize to voters who signed a petition against \'93activist judges.\'94 One Wisconsin voter was publicly awarded $1 million. State officials called the scheme corrupt, and the Wisconsin Department of Justice prepared legal action, but the episode showed how corporate wealth could be used to shape both law enforcement priorities and judicial composition.\
