Universities found themselves squeezed between federal power and private influence. Columbia University faced the withholding of $400 million in federal grants until it complied with administration demands over alleged antisemitism and protest handling. Columbia faculty and unions sued over cuts to public health research funding. Academic associations sued to protect foreign students from deportation tied to their political views. The University of Michigan dismantled its DEI infrastructure under federal pressure. These were not isolated disputes over campus speech. They were part of a broader campaign in which universities were told, in effect, to suppress certain forms of dissent or lose funding and face immigration crackdowns on their students. Higher education was being pressed into line.\
