Even as these pressures mounted, pockets of resistance remained. Federal judges blocked the administration\'92s attempt to enforce a ban on transgender military service, calling the self\uc0\u8209 reporting requirement an invasion of privacy. Appeals courts upheld orders requiring the rehiring of thousands of federal workers fired in mass reductions, and refused to lift blocks on deportations under the Alien Enemies Act. A district judge stopped the termination of funding for Radio Free Europe. The Supreme Court declined to revisit New York Times v. Sullivan, preserving the \'93actual malice\'94 standard that protects press freedom. State actors, too, pushed back: the Wisconsin Department of Justice moved against Musk\'92s election scheme, and Democratic victories in a Pennsylvania state senate race suggested that voters in some Trump\u8209 leaning districts were open to alternatives. These acts did not reverse the week\'92s structural shifts, but they showed that the system still contained levers that could be pulled.\
