By the close of Week 10, the Democracy Clock\'92s move to 7:49 p.m. captured a democracy that was not yet formally broken but was being refitted so that it could be ruled with less consent and more fear. Executive orders had become the primary tool of governance, reaching into elections, labor rights, education, culture, and local policing. Law was increasingly something to be aimed\'97at law firms, judges, immigrants, students\'97rather than a boundary that constrained power. The civil service was being stripped of its protections and repopulated with loyalists or left hollow, even as public health and social welfare were cut back. Surveillance expanded downward, while secrecy and chaos shielded those at the top. History and memory were curated from the center, with museums, universities, and public media told which stories could be told.\
